/////////////////////pointer-to-pointer-to-pointer
#include<stdio.h>
#include<string.h>
int main()
{

static char *s[]={"black","white","pink","violet"};
char **ptr[]={s+3,s+2,s+1,s},***p;
p = ptr;
printf("%s\n",**p+1);
return 0;
}



///////////////////
2️⃣ Understanding array s
static char *s[]={"black","white","pink","violet"};

s is an array of pointers to strings.

Memory conceptually:

s[0] → "black"
s[1] → "white"
s[2] → "pink"
s[3] → "violet"
3️⃣ Understanding ptr
char **ptr[]={s+3,s+2,s+1,s};

Each element of ptr stores an address inside array s.

s+3 → &s[3]
s+2 → &s[2]
s+1 → &s[1]
s   → &s[0]

So:

ptr[0] → s+3 → &s[3]
ptr[1] → s+2 → &s[2]
ptr[2] → s+1 → &s[1]
ptr[3] → s   → &s[0]

Visual:

ptr
│
├─ ptr[0] → &s[3] → "violet"
├─ ptr[1] → &s[2] → "pink"
├─ ptr[2] → &s[1] → "white"
└─ ptr[3] → &s[0] → "black"
4️⃣ Pointer p
char ***p;
p = ptr;

So:

p → ptr[0]
5️⃣ Evaluate **p

Step by step:

p → ptr[0]
*p → s+3
**p → s[3]
s[3] → "violet"
6️⃣ Expression **p + 1

**p is the string:

"violet"

Adding +1 moves pointer one character ahead.

"violet"
 ^
  +1

New string:

iolet
7️⃣ printf
printf("%s\n",**p+1);

So it prints:

iolet
8️⃣ Final Output
iolet
9️⃣ Key Pointer Levels
Expression	Meaning
p	pointer to pointer to pointer
*p	pointer to pointer
**p	pointer to string
**p + 1	second character of string
🔟 Important Interview Concept
**p = s[3] = "violet"
**p + 1 → "iolet"
